Types of Loss Functions with Examples
A loss function measures how much the predicted output differs from the actual output.
The goal of training is to minimize the loss.
Common Types of Loss Functions
Loss Function	Used For	Example
Mean Squared Error (MSE)	Regression	House price prediction
Mean Absolute Error (MAE)	Regression	Temperature prediction
Binary Crossentropy	Binary classification	Spam detection
Categorical Crossentropy	Multiclass classification	Digit recognition
Sparse Categorical Crossentropy	Multiclass with integer labels	MNIST labels
Hinge Loss	SVM models	Margin classification
Mean Squared Error (MSE)
Used in regression problems.
Formula:
MSE=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2
Where:
(y_i) = actual value
(\hat{y}_i) = predicted value
Example
Actual price = 100
Predicted price = 90
Error:
(100 - 90)² = 100
Large errors get heavily penalized.
Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
Used in regression.
Formula:
MAE=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}|y_i-\hat{y}_i|
Example
Actual = 100
Predicted = 90
Error:
|100 - 90| = 10
Less sensitive to outliers than MSE.
Binary Crossentropy
Used for binary classification.
Formula:
L=-\left(y\log(\hat{y})+(1-y)\log(1-\hat{y})\right)
Example
Sentiment analysis
Spam detection
Output:
0 → Negative
1 → Positive

Categorical Crossentropy
Used for multiclass classification.
Formula:
L=-\sum_{i=1}^{C} y_i\log(\hat{y}_i)
Example
Classifying:
Cat
Dog
Horse
Sparse Categorical Crossentropy
Same as categorical crossentropy but labels are integers.
Example:
0,1,2,3
instead of one-hot encoding.
What are L1 and L2 Loss Functions?
L1 and L2 are error measurement methods and also used in regularization.

L1 Loss (Least Absolute Deviations)
Formula:
L1=\sum |y-\hat{y}|
It calculates absolute differences.

Example
Actual = 20
Predicted = 15
L1 Loss:
|20 - 15| = 5
Characteristics of L1 Loss
Feature	Description
Uses absolute values	Yes
Sensitive to outliers	Less
Produces sparse models	Yes
Easier interpretation	Yes

L2 Loss (Least Squares Error)
Formula:
L2=\sum (y-\hat{y})^2
Squares the errors.

Example
Actual = 20
Predicted = 15
L2 Loss:
(20 - 15)² = 25
Characteristics of L2 Loss
Feature	Description
Uses squared errors	Yes
Sensitive to outliers	More
Smooth optimization	Yes
Most commonly used	Yes

Difference Between L1 and L2
Feature	L1 Loss	L2 Loss
Formula	Absolute error	Squared error
Outlier sensitivity	Low	High
Produces sparse weights	Yes	No
Optimization	Harder	Easier
Example	MAE	MSE

